Kenya’s World 10,000m Under-20 champion, Rhonex Kipruto and World U20 3, 000m steeplechase champion Celliphine Chepteek are among 10 youngsters shortlisted for the 2018 IAAF Rising Star Award. The 19-year-old Kipruto, who is also the African junior cross-country champion, will battle it out with Ethiopia’s Selemon Barega, jumper Jordan Diaz from Cuba, World U20 pole-vault champion Armand Duplantis from Sweden and Jakob Ingebrigtsen from Norway. Kipruto had a fantastic 2018 season, setting a world 10,000m lead of 27:21:08 enroute winning gold in the 25-lap event at the IAAF World U-20 Championships. He also holds two world U-20 bests and world senior lead at road 10km with 26:46, just two seconds outside the senior world record. Chepteek on her part, set a world U20 lead in steeplechase with 9:01.82 in addition to the world title. She is also the African (senior) cross-country champion and grabbed silvers at the Commonwealth Games and African Championships. Chepteek will battle it out with Ethiopia’s Meseret Belete and Meskerem Mamo, Sydney McLaughlin (USA) and Briana Williams (Jamaica). The winner will be announced live on stage at the IAAF Athletics Awards 2018 in Monaco on December 4. Also nominated from Kenya is world marathon record holder Eliud Kipchoge in the IAAF Male Athlete of the Year category. Kipchoge set a new marathon world record in Berlin in September, clocking 2:01:39 to shave one minute, 18 seconds off the old mark set by Dennis Kimetto in 2014 at the same venue. Another Kenya Emmanuel Korir will also be gunning for the middle distance gong during the gala. The student of the University of El Paso Texas clocked the fastest time this year in the 800m at the Diamond League event in London, where he posted 1:42.05 in July. He anchored the Kenya relay 4x400m team at the Africa Championships in Asaba, where they bagged gold. Commonwealth Games 1,500m silver medallist, Timothy Cheruiyot is also included in the top ten after stellar season. Cheruiyot had world leads in the 1,500m, where he clocked 3:28.41 set in Monaco and the mile at 3:49.64 set in Oregon in May at the Prefontaine Classic.He also won silver over the distance at the Africa Championship in Asaba in August. World 3,000m steeplechase record holder, Beatrice Chepkoech has been nominated in the ladies category. Chepkoech clocked 8:44.32 to set a new world record in the water jump event in Monaco in July.